      <scopecontent id="aspace_27215a5742009168270c67cd42d0c08a">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The Greater New Haven Chamber of Commerce Committee Records primarily document the history of urban planning and zoning of the New Haven region from 1946 to 1964. The collection contains correspondence, memos, meeting minutes, survey results, planning documents, and budget sheets, along with other documentation from the Chamber's various committees. Records include information regarding New Haven mayors William C. Celentano and Richard C. Lee as well as leading transportation expert Kent T. Healy and their involvement in urban zoning.</p>
         <p>This collection includes ideas by W. Ogden Ross, a well-known New Haven businessman, who served as the Chamber's public relations director.</p>
         <p>Records related to the Chamber's Industrial Development Committee document discussions about the rerouting of U.S. Route 1 and development of Interstate 95 (I-95).</p>
         <p>Records related to the Chamber's Parking and Traffic Committee document discussions about increased investments in public transit in reaction to the declining revenue during the 1950s, including the updating of trolley systems, the creation of bus lanes, the expansion of Tweed Airport, and the widening of the roads in downtown New Haven.</p>
         <p>Records related to the Chamber's Harbor Development Committee document the dredging of the city's port during the 1950s to allow for greater use of New Haven Harbor.</p>
         <p>The records also document the Chamber's prioritization of the development of existing industries based in New Haven, as well as the recruitment of new businesses in manufacturing and supply. Among them were Atlantic Wire Company, Norwalk Tire Company, Griest Manufacturing Company, U.S. Electrical Motors, and U.S. Aluminum Smelting Company.</p>
         <p>Lastly, the records document the Chamber's Redevelopment Committee, which was created after Mayor Richard C. Lee raised concerns about declining areas of the city. Meeting minutes show that nearly two dozen families living in predominately Black neighborhoods were displaced due to the redevelopment of residential areas and their conversion into business districts during Lee's mayorship.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      <bioghist id="aspace_6246421ba169669d15f55bf4a9758e08">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>The Greater New Haven Chamber of Commerce, founded in 1794, promotes economic growth and development of the New Haven region of Connecticut by advocating for businesses and economic legislations.  It was the second chamber of commerce in the United States.  The organization started with 26 prominent New Haven residents, who lobbied against British and French control of the city's ports during the French Revolutionary Wars.  Among the founding members were Eli Whitney, Noah Webster, and Timothy Dwight.  Its headquarters are located in New Haven, Connecticut. The Chamber supports the Connecticut towns of Woodbridge, Wallingford, Orange, North Haven, North Branford, Milford, Meriden, Madison, Guilford, East Haven, Cheshire, Branford, Bethany, Hamden, and West Haven.</p>
      </bioghist>
